listitem.para:
it can be used as a simple, basic CMS. The user interface allows
        to edit pages visually, add and delete pages and do other basic tasks.
        This kind of approach should be easy enough for everyone;

multi-site support - multiple
        sites can be served with a single installation on a single
        context;

compatible with other editors -
        since it is file-based, you can edit your files with other programs if
        you want, then upload them as usual;

support for themes - uses
        SiteMesh as
        engine;

tag library to create new
        themes easily - menus and other common components are created
        automatically;

messages: contains a
                  copy of the e-mail messages that are sent through mail
                  forms;

filetypes.txt:
                  contains a database of file types; fields are
                  tab-separated;

the theme main file: a JSP page named
          main.jsp that defines the common part of the
          pages and where the variable parts must be inserted;

the reset field inserts a reset button. A
          label can be specified as for the submit
          button;

open the File Manager and
          create a new HTML file in the desired place. Please keep in mind how
          the site map is created;

mode: the type of breadcrumbs. Possible
          values are titles (default) and
          links;

current: boolean value to
          include/exclude the current page (default is
          true);

pre: a text to be added before the
          first element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
          all;

current: boolean value to
          include/exclude the current page (default is
          true);

pre: a text to be added before the
          first element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
          all;

style: a css style. This is passed to
          the include template and might be used or not (for example
          Include uses it). Default is no style;

location (required): the name of the
          module location. All modules in a theme must have
          different location names;

date: the format of the date. Possible
          values are normal (default) and
          full;
